<subSubSection pageId="145" pageNumber="146" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,2015]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1521,1547]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Etymology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[344,436,1521,1547]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis box="[344,436,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Serratia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(feminine) is a noun latinised from the English word serrate reflecting the nature of the antennal segments in the male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="146" lastPageNumber="147" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,2015]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1593,1619]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Remarks.</emphasis>
We know of four 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1857" box="[517,637,1593,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciolinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luciolinae</taxonomicName>
species described as having serrate or flattened antennae. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker)" authorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Luciola intricata</emphasis>
(Walker)
</taxonomicName>
has FS 2–8 serrate. It is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[831,879,1629,1655]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">type</typeStatus>
which is missing the abdomen, and while treated here as 
<emphasis box="[234,413,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">species incertae</emphasis>
it is characterized from certain other features. 
<taxonomicName box="[926,1018,1665,1691]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis box="[926,1018,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Serratia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1023,1115,1665,1691]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">gen nov</emphasis>
. differs most obviously from those features of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[346,473,1702,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis box="[346,473,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">L. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
we could determine in the number of, and outline of, the laterally produced antennal flagellar segments, and the nature of the apical labial palpomere (that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[969,1095,1738,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intricata">
<emphasis box="[969,1095,1738,1763]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">L. intricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is broadly flattened and triangular, with the inner margin dentate).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,2015]" lastBlockId="146.[151,1437,152,287]" lastPageId="146" lastPageNumber="147" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<bibRefCitation author="Olivier" box="[199,361,1809,1836]" firstAuthor="Olivier" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" pagination="183 - 187" refId="ref120180" refString="Olivier, E. (1886) In: Baer, G. - A., Catalogue des Coleopteres des Iles Philippines. Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 1886, 183 - 187." type="journal article" year="1886">Olivier (1886)</bibRefCitation>
described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1886" box="[516,710,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exstincta">
<emphasis box="[516,710,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Luciola exstincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a single female from Alitaptap (
<collectingCountry box="[1078,1208,1809,1836]" name="Philippines" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Philippines</collectingCountry>
) which is of similar size but different colouration to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ho, 2019" authorityName="Ho" authorityYear="2019" box="[514,722,1845,1871]" class="Gammaproteobacteria" family="Enterobacteriaceae" genus="Serratia" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Enterobacteriales" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Proteobacteria" rank="species" species="sibuyania" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[514,722,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Serratia sibuyania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[730,905,1845,1871]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[730,778,1845,1871]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">gen.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[786,806,1846,1871]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">et</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[814,899,1845,1871]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and in which the antennal ‘articulis 4–8’ were expanded. It is unclear if Olivier was referring to the flagellar segments only (as we do here), or more likely to the antennal segments counting the scape as number 1. If the latter then his reference is to flagellar segments 2–6 which is not inconsistent with what we describe here. We cannot locate the 
<typeStatus box="[923,971,1953,1979]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">type</typeStatus>
of this species and it is difficult to assign males to any species described from a female only. Antennal modifications in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lacordaire" authorityYear="1857" box="[1066,1186,1989,2015]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciolinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="145" pageNumber="166" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luciolinae</taxonomicName>
are more usually seen in males (
<bibRefCitation author="Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin" box="[258,582,153,179]" firstAuthor="Ballantyne" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref114597" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; Lambkin, C. L. (2013) Systematics and phylogenetics of Indo-Pacific Luciolinae fireflies (Coleoptera: Lampyridae) and the description of new genera. Zootaxa, 3653 (1), 1 - 162. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3653.1.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Bourgeois" box="[600,795,152,179]" firstAuthor="Bourgeois" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" pagination="127" refId="ref115516" refString="Bourgeois, J. (1905) Voyage du D. W. Horn a Ceylan. Malacodermes et Lymexylonides. II. Lampyridini. Annales de la Societe entomologique de France, 74, 127." type="journal article" year="1905">Bourgeois (1905)</bibRefCitation>
described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1905" box="[943,1089,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="146" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="antennalis">
<emphasis box="[943,1089,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">L. antennalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a single female from 
<collectingCountry box="[1328,1436,153,179]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
as dorsally yellow with antennal segments 4−7 depressed. The 
<typeStatus box="[862,910,189,215]" pageId="146" pageNumber="147">type</typeStatus>
has not been located but the description of the antennal segments appears consistent with what we describe here. Bourgeois considered, and we agree, “elle mériterait peut-être de constituer un genre nouveau’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
